Corvinus (the ‘Messalla’ of Sat. 1. 6. 42, 1. 10. 85, A. P. 371 ‘diserti Mes· ‚ sallae' ) was, like Pollio, at once distinguished in the political and the literary world. He had belonged to the senatorian party, and turned Octavius’ flank m the first day's fighting at Philippi. He subsequently joined Octavius against Antony, and commanded the centre of his fleet at Actium. After the settlement he retired from active life, and devoted himself to oratory and literature. He was

the great friend and patron of Tibullus.
